# Markdown tables

When creating or editing Markdown tables, always **prettify** them so columns are aligned and easy to scan in source.

## Required style

1. Put one space after each opening `|` and one space before each closing `|`.
2. Pad cell content with spaces so every column has a consistent width (based on the widest cell in that column, including the header).
3. Make the separator row (`---`) match each column width (at least three dashes).
4. Prefer left-aligned columns (`---` / `:---`). Use `:---` / `:---:` / `---:` only when alignment is intentional.
5. Keep one logical row per line; do not wrap cell text across lines.
6. When you touch an existing table (even for a small edit), re-prettify the whole table.

## Example

Bad:

```markdown
| Site | URL | What you get |
| ---- | --- | ------------ |
| Project site | [regenfass.eu](https://regenfass.eu) | Overview |
| Docs | [docs.regenfass.eu](https://docs.regenfass.eu) | Guides |
```

Good:

```markdown
| Site         | URL                                            | What you get |
| ------------ | ---------------------------------------------- | ------------ |
| Project site | [regenfass.eu](https://regenfass.eu)           | Overview     |
| Docs         | [docs.regenfass.eu](https://docs.regenfass.eu) | Guides       |
```

## Scope

Applies to all Markdown sources agents write or change (`README.md`, `docs/`, `web/*/docs`, `.agents/`, etc.). Do not leave compact, ragged tables in diffs you introduce.
